      "id": 76,
      "title": "Artemis II Splashdown Live: What’s Happening",
      "slug": "artemis-ii-splashdown-live-whats-happening",
      "excerpt": "The NASA Artemis II splashdown is where everything comes down to seconds. After a high-speed return from the Moon, the Orion spacecraft tears through Earth’s atmosphere, endures extreme heat, and deploys parachutes before landing in the Pacific Ocean. It’s tense, precise, and unforgiving-but if it works, it clears the path for humanity’s return to the lunar surface.",
      "content": "<h2>NASA Artemis II Splashdown - Live Report Style</h2>\n<p><strong>The <span><span>NASA Artemis II</span></span> crew is coming home fast. Really fast. After looping the Moon, they’ll slam into Earth’s atmosphere, ride out a firestorm, and hit the Pacific under parachutes. Everything hinges on those final minutes.</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Quick Take</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>\nCrew returns from lunar flyby after ~10 days\n</li>\n<li>\nReentry speed: ~40,000 km/h\n</li>\n<li>\nHeat shield faces extreme temperatures\n</li>\n<li>\nParachutes deploy in stages - no room for error\n</li>\n<li>\nSplashdown in Pacific Ocean\n</li>\n<li>\nRecovery teams move in within minutes\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>Reentry Has Begun</h3>\n<div><div><div><button><div><img src=\"https://images.openai.com/static-rsc-4/1mhwnkXra4QqPo4prcdPiAPi9EKMlsXCt8xsOTVVu8r6HjOQuB_doIy6Gj2RrSM_s-nW4yE6ops6IeA4jxisL3DEeWrPe7CUMWIxn5Us6Ghj73piJ0pcarwfgsjXM20JKdN2CJ_BYiudOITo23dWiGxgkvKNVEIwviXlaIDuKjU?purpose=inline\"></div></button></div></div><div><div><button><div><br></div></button><br></div><br></div><div><div><button><div><img src=\"https://images.openai.com/static-rsc-4/tjntN4RmbCwVJnxUM6UtCKtnhVQ4VtI2iiXaVyO-fkPu-L6xebpdvzTxtNvD-ywMScvCGZh4-4z7pj4VNagDcHr1mxH7WintLGRwTznQgyXFj6Pe17N5d6d1Zh4UMBIA-iGZKqtZmIhntEktSZIkE5-IQdIqGmPa9-M8E7HcWaFqErqtV7PuHnyJKjEqP1Ci?purpose=inline\"></div></button></div></div></div>\n<p>You’re watching it happen.</p>\n<p>The <span><span>Orion spacecraft</span></span> hits the upper atmosphere. Speed is brutal. The capsule starts to glow. Plasma builds. Communication drops.</p>\n<p>Silence.</p>\n<p>That blackout? Expected. Still tense every time.</p>\n<p>Inside, the crew is strapped in. No view. Just vibration and heat shielding doing its job.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>The Most Dangerous Minutes</h3>\n<p>This is where missions are won-or lost.</p>\n<p>The heat shield takes the full force. Temperatures spike past 2,700°C. The spacecraft slows, but not gently.</p>\n<p>Then-movement changes.</p>\n<p>Drogue parachutes deploy. Small, but critical. They stabilize the capsule.</p>\n<p>Seconds later, main parachutes burst open.</p>\n<p>Big. White. Powerful.</p>\n<p>Speed drops fast.</p>\n<p>You can almost feel the tension ease.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Crew on Board</h3>\n<div><div><div><button><div><img src=\"https://images.openai.com/static-rsc-4/gsC-X6knfWxNJMUS0zFd9GEM8WJM92iQpGRZtxQkh0DOeno1Y3MQBgiYnPdWnZUiASNhk9QmO4jgkcVnfPh4pU0W7cY6LSyed39un8Nuho9EBNLNLwi8l3nmUtr2d7zG5HmPP49JdeP7hiMLbkorp-bNzh5mPoTR26Wnsb_PLT8?purpose=inline\"></div></button></div></div>Inside Orion:</div>\n\n<ul>\n<li>\n<span><span>Reid Wiseman</span></span>\n</li>\n<li>\n<span><span>Victor Glover</span></span>\n</li>\n<li>\n<span><span>Christina Koch</span></span>\n</li>\n<li>\n<span><span>Jeremy Hansen</span></span>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Four astronauts. One capsule. No second chances during reentry.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Also Read -&nbsp;<u><a href=\"https://beansnews.com/world-news/epstein-files-client-list-what-theyre-hiding\">Epstein Files Client List: What They’re Hiding</a></u></strong></p><p><strong><u><br></u></strong></p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Splashdown</h3>\n<p>Impact.</p>\n<p>Not violent-but not soft either.</p>\n<p>The capsule hits the Pacific Ocean. Water sprays. The parachutes collapse around it.</p>\n<p>For a moment, it just floats there.</p>\n<p>Mission almost complete.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Recovery Teams Move In</h3>\n<div><div><div><button><div><img src=\"https://images.openai.com/static-rsc-4/tjntN4RmbCwVJnxUM6UtCKtnhVQ4VtI2iiXaVyO-fkPu-L6xebpdvzTxtNvD-ywMScvCGZh4-4z7pj4VNagDcHr1mxH7WintLGRwTznQgyXFj6Pe17N5d6d1Zh4UMBIA-iGZKqtZmIhntEktSZIkE5-IQdIqGmPa9-M8E7HcWaFqErqtV7PuHnyJKjEqP1Ci?purpose=inline\"></div></button></div></div><div><div><button><div><br></div></button><br></div><br></div><div><div><button><div><img src=\"https://images.openai.com/static-rsc-4/oloRR_HUy1sRD1_K7xOpYDT-wS-rKAWEQz2tF_YM0-VhI3Ics-ZymYcETDcl-kVzjRCgt2JkNSk5SmWQgpV8sE_W2_-ZGGiVUnkSTeSxqfjn_Mvu59wTFknjx9nQlC_DpYl9pJgrdptUlTtBiuLkrq-enDx_GRZQFtDvhDjqWRJ-OSt7p3vSHB7-xJQuvLTj?purpose=inline\"></div></button></div></div></div>\n<p>Now it’s a race.</p>\n<p>Divers jump in. They secure the capsule. Attach flotation gear.</p>\n<p>Helicopters circle overhead.</p>\n<p>The hatch opens.</p>\n<p>Astronauts come out one by one. Slow. Careful. Gravity hits differently after days in space.</p>\n<p>Medical teams step in immediately.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Why This Moment Matters</h3>\n<p>This isn’t just a landing.</p>\n<p>It’s proof.</p>\n<p>Proof that <span><span>NASA</span></span> can send humans beyond low Earth orbit—and bring them back safely.</p>\n<p>It clears the path for <span><span>NASA Artemis III</span></span>.</p>\n<p>Moon landings. Lunar bases. Mars, eventually.</p>\n<p>But none of that happens if this ending fails.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>What Engineers Really Think</h3>\n<p>Here’s something most people don’t realize:</p>\n<p>Launch looks dramatic. Reentry is what keeps engineers up at night.</p>\n<p>One missed sequence. One failed chute. That’s it.</p>\n<p>Everything comes down to these final minutes.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Quick Answers (People Also Ask)</h3>\n<p><strong>What is splashdown?</strong><br>\nA controlled ocean landing using parachutes after atmospheric reentry.</p>\n<p><strong>Where does Artemis II land?</strong><br>\nPacific Ocean, with Navy and NASA recovery teams waiting.</p>\n<p><strong>Why not land on land?</strong><br>\nWater reduces impact risk and gives flexible landing zones.</p>\n<p><strong>How fast is reentry?</strong><br>\nAround 40,000 km/h-faster than most spacecraft returns.</p>",
